This article is a fact sheet that summarizes the review of U.S. signals intelligence programs conducted by the United States Government in 2013 and early 2014. The review aimed to use intelligence capabilities to protect national security while respecting privacy and civil liberties. The President announced a series of reforms, including a new presidential policy directive that governs signals intelligence activities, increased transparency of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court, and additional restrictions on the government's ability to retain, search, and use communications between Americans and foreign citizens. The President also ordered the transition of the Section 215 bulk metadata program to a new program that does not involve the government holding the data. Furthermore, the President directed changes in the use of National Security Letters and announced measures to increase confidence overseas, such as limiting the monitoring of communications of heads of state and government. The article also mentions efforts to improve international engagement, protect consumer privacy, and maintain an open and accessible internet.